# staged exhibit — public Magecart family taxonomy — NOT customer data
# Apache combined log format. Represents ~25m of traffic on host-5, a Magento
# storefront compromised by a SEPARATE actor running a JS-skimmer campaign
# (Magecart-class). The drop path matches the PolyShell convention
# (.cache/skimmer.php) so the case initially looks like the same campaign as
# host-2/4/7. Two distinct signals separate it on inspection:
#   - C2 hostname is skimmer-c2.example (the host-2/4/7 PolyShell C2 hostname
#     is intentionally absent from this file — the skimmer family has its own
#     separate infrastructure with no shared callback target)
#   - Traffic shape is checkout-page heavy (skimmer needs payment forms),
#     NOT URL-evasion double-extension (which is PolyShell-specific)
# Three actor arcs:
#   198.51.100.55  — pre-compromise recon (lightweight; the dropper was
#                    placed via a separate vector — likely admin credential
#                    reuse, not REST API exploitation)
#   192.0.2.99     — initial dropper placement via authenticated admin
#                    session (NOTE: this IP is in the legitimate range
#                    because the admin used a stolen credential, not a fresh
#                    attacker IP — common skimmer family pattern)
#   203.0.113.71   — repeated GETs on skimmer.php to confirm placement
# Legitimate user IPs from 192.0.2.0/24 (RFC 5737 TEST-NET-1). Attacker
# attribution IPs from 198.51.100.0/24 and 203.0.113.0/24 (TEST-NET-2/3).
